Trespasses, as might be expected, on the neigh- bour's oorn, when the open-field system of cultivation was in use, are frequent. Hirsill, or the obligation of the tenants to send their cattle, gesse, and pigs from the vill under proper oustody‚ would obviate to some extent the want of fences3 but we oonstantly find hot disputes among the tenants from this cause, which often led first to hard words and then to blows. Indeed, the frequent orders upon the tenants not to transgress in word or deed, or with stares, arrows or knives, and the numerous fines for drawing knives to strike, and (though less frequently) striking with knives, 'and the volu· bility of the villana in court, rather suggest some points of resemblance between the tenants of the Prior and the peasantry of to-day in our sister isle. Attendanoe at the lord's court was strictly enforoed, and the fines for absence, or being late, are frequent. Contempt of court was not unknown ; thus we find fines imposed for refusing to be silent in court, speaking contemptu- ously of the jury, and imputing to them falsehood. Brewing of beer appears to have been farmed from the Prior. It was therefore necessary to give brewers protection, and accordingly we find it an offence to buy beer outside the vill and sell it within. In Shields
